# JavaScript/TypeScript Coding Standards

## Code Style & Formatting
- Follow Airbnb JavaScript Style Guide
- Use 2 spaces for indentation
- Maximum line length of 100 characters
- Use single quotes for strings consistently
- Always use semicolons
- Add trailing commas in multi-line structures

## Modern JavaScript (ES6+)
- Use `const` and `let` instead of `var`
- Prefer arrow functions for callbacks and short functions
- Use template literals (backticks) for string interpolation
- Use destructuring assignment for objects and arrays
- Use spread operator `...` instead of `Object.assign()`
- Use async/await instead of Promise chains when possible

## Naming Conventions
- Use `camelCase` for variables, functions, and methods
- Use `PascalCase` for classes, constructors, and React components
- Use `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` for constants
- Use descriptive names that clearly indicate purpose
- Prefix private methods with underscore `_` (or use # for true private fields)

## TypeScript Specific
- Always define explicit types for function parameters and return values
- Use interfaces for object shapes and contracts
- Use type aliases for complex types
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object definitions
- Use generics for reusable components and functions
- Enable strict mode in tsconfig.json

## Functions & Methods
- Keep functions small and focused (single responsibility)
- Use pure functions when possible (no side effects)
- Always return a value or explicitly return `undefined`
- Use default parameters instead of checking for `undefined`
- Prefer function declarations for named functions
- Use arrow functions for anonymous functions and callbacks

## Error Handling
- Use try/catch blocks for error handling
- Throw meaningful Error objects with descriptive messages
- Use proper error types (TypeError, RangeError, etc.)
- Implement proper logging and error reporting
- Handle Promise rejections appropriately

## Async Programming
- Use async/await for asynchronous operations
- Handle errors in async functions with try/catch
- Use Promise.all() for concurrent operations
- Avoid callback hell, prefer Promises or async/await
- Use proper error handling for async operations

## Code Organization
- Use ES6 modules (import/export) consistently
- Group imports: external libraries, internal modules, relative imports
- Export default for single-purpose modules
- Use named exports for utilities and multiple exports
- Organize code into logical modules and directories

## React/JSX Specific (if applicable)
- Use functional components with hooks instead of class components
- Follow hooks rules (only call at top level, only in React functions)
- Use PascalCase for component names
- Use camelCase for prop names
- Always use key prop in lists
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Use PropTypes or TypeScript for prop validation

## Performance & Best Practices
- Avoid global variables
- Use strict equality (`===`) instead of loose equality (`==`)
- Minimize DOM manipulation, batch updates when possible
- Use event delegation for dynamic content
- Implement proper memory management (remove event listeners)
- Use appropriate data structures (Map, Set, WeakMap, WeakSet)

## Testing
- Write unit tests using Jest or similar framework
- Use descriptive test names that explain the expected behavior
- Follow AAA pattern: Arrange, Act, Assert
- Mock external dependencies appropriately
- Test both happy path and error cases
- Aim for high test coverage

## Node.js Specific (if applicable)
- Use proper error-first callback pattern
- Handle uncaught exceptions and unhandled rejections
- Use environment variables for configuration
- Implement proper logging with levels
- Use middleware pattern for Express.js applications
- Follow security best practices (helmet, rate limiting, etc.)